cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.LG, cs.IR, cs.CL 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it deals with predicting information spread on social media platforms. It could also belong to cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) as it involves modeling social structures and homophily. Additionally, the paper utilizes machine learning techniques such as variational autoencoders and graph neural networks, which are commonly used in sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper involves predicting influenced users, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval).
